  "summary": "Drafts a comprehensive Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) governing the sale and purchase of electrical power between generators and offtakers. Ensures legal soundness, commercial balance, and compliance with energy regulations and industry standards like NREL and EFET. Use for regulatory energy law matters involving renewable or power generation projects.",
  "content": "# Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) Drafting Workflow\n\nYou are tasked with drafting a comprehensive Power Purchase Agreement (PPA), a critical regulatory document governing the sale and purchase of electrical power between a generator (seller) and an offtaker (buyer). This agreement must be legally sound, commercially balanced, and compliant with applicable energy regulations and industry standards.\n\n## Document Preparation and Research Strategy\n\nBegin by conducting thorough research to gather all necessary information for the agreement. Search the user's uploaded documents to identify specific project details, party information, technical specifications, and any existing agreements or correspondence that may inform the PPA structure. Look for concrete facts including company names, addresses, project capacity, location details, pricing discussions, and timeline information.\n\nSupplement document-specific information with authoritative external sources. Research current industry standards and best practices from recognized authorities including the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL), World Bank PPA templates, International Emissions Trading Association (IETA), European Federation of Energy Traders (EFET), and the International Swaps and Derivatives Association (ISDA). Verify legal requirements and standard clauses through state bar association resources and energy regulatory authorities.\n\n## Core Agreement Structure and Content\n\n**Parties and Recitals**: Establish the legal foundation by precisely identifying the buyer (offtaker) and seller (generator) with complete legal names, registered addresses, jurisdiction of incorporation, and designated roles under the agreement. Draft comprehensive recitals that provide essential background including the project description, generation facility specifications, the commercial purpose of the agreement, regulatory context, and the effective date. Ensure the recitals create a clear narrative that supports the operative provisions.\n\n**Definitions and Interpretation**: Create a robust definitions section that establishes precise meanings for all technical, commercial, and legal terms used throughout the agreement. Essential definitions must include Capacity (measured in MW or kW), Energy (measured in MWh or kWh), Net Output, Delivered Energy, Contract Price, Force Majeure, Commercial Operation Date, Scheduled Maintenance, and Availability. Reference industry-standard definitions from EFET, ISDA, or relevant grid codes to ensure consistency with market practice and regulatory expectations.\n\n**Term and Conditions Precedent**: Specify the agreement duration, typically ranging from 10 to 25 years for renewable energy projects, with clear commencement and expiration dates. Detail all conditions precedent that must be satisfied before the agreement becomes effective, which may include obtaining necessary permits and licenses, achieving financial close, securing grid connection agreements, completing construction milestones, and obtaining required insurance coverage. Establish realistic deadlines for satisfying conditions precedent and consequences for failure to meet them.\n\n**Purchase and Sale Obligations**: Articulate the seller's absolute obligation to generate and deliver electrical energy to the delivery point, and the buyer's corresponding obligation to purchase all or a specified portion of the delivered energy. Address capacity obligations, minimum and maximum delivery quantities, scheduling and dispatch procedures, and curtailment rights. Ensure the obligations reflect the specific project type (baseload, intermittent renewable, dispatchable) and any regulatory requirements such as renewable energy certificate (REC) delivery or carbon attribute transfer.\n\n**Pricing, Payment, and Invoicing**: Establish a clear and comprehensive pricing mechanism that may be structured as fixed pricing (cents per kWh), indexed pricing (tied to inflation or commodity indices), time-of-delivery pricing (varying by time of day or season), or capacity payments plus energy payments. Detail the complete payment process including billing cycles (typically monthly), invoice requirements and supporting documentation, payment due dates (commonly 30 days from invoice), late payment interest calculations, and payment methods. Address tax treatment, including which party bears responsibility for various taxes and how tax changes will be handled.\n\n**Metering, Measurement, and Verification**: Specify technical requirements for metering equipment including accuracy standards (typically \u00b10.5% or better), testing and calibration schedules (often quarterly or annually), and compliance with relevant grid codes or ISO standards. Establish procedures for meter reading, data collection and transmission, dispute resolution regarding meter accuracy, and replacement of faulty equipment. Address energy loss calculations and allocation between the delivery point and the point of interconnection.\n\n**Representations, Warranties, and Covenants**: Include comprehensive representations and warranties from both parties covering corporate authority and capacity to enter the agreement, due authorization and enforceability, absence of conflicts with other agreements or court orders, compliance with applicable laws and regulations, possession of necessary permits and licenses, and financial capability to perform obligations. Add ongoing covenants requiring maintenance of permits, compliance with laws, maintenance of insurance, and provision of regular operational and financial reports.\n\n**Performance Standards and Liquidated Damages**: Establish clear performance metrics including minimum availability requirements (often 90-95% annually), capacity factor targets for renewable projects, and energy delivery guarantees. Specify liquidated damages or performance penalties for failure to meet these standards, ensuring they represent a genuine pre-estimate of loss rather than a penalty. Include cure periods and force majeure exceptions to performance obligations.\n\n**Events of Default and Remedies**: Comprehensively define events of default including payment defaults (typically after a cure period of 5-10 business days), material breach of representations or covenants, bankruptcy or insolvency proceedings, failure to maintain required insurance or security, abandonment of the facility, and cross-default to project financing agreements. Specify remedies available to the non-defaulting party including termination rights, damages calculations (cover damages, replacement power costs, or termination payments), and rights to step-in or cure defaults. Ensure remedy provisions comply with applicable law regarding penalty clauses and liquidated damages.\n\n**Force Majeure**: Define force majeure events that excuse performance, typically including natural disasters, acts of God, war, terrorism, strikes, changes in law, and grid or transmission system failures beyond the party's control. Specify that force majeure events must be unforeseeable, beyond reasonable control, and not caused by the claiming party's negligence. Establish notice requirements, mitigation obligations, and the effect on payment and delivery obligations during force majeure periods. Address extended force majeure scenarios that may give rise to termination rights if the event persists beyond a specified period (commonly 6-12 months).\n\n**Insurance and Security**: Detail insurance requirements for both parties including commercial general liability, property insurance for the facility, business interruption insurance, and professional indemnity coverage. Specify minimum coverage amounts, required endorsements, and proof of insurance delivery requirements. Address security requirements such as letters of credit, parent guarantees, or cash deposits to secure performance obligations, particularly during construction or for creditworthy concerns.\n\n**Termination and Consequences**: Establish termination rights beyond default scenarios, including termination for convenience (if applicable), regulatory change making performance illegal or commercially impracticable, and mutual agreement. Specify notice periods for termination (typically 30-90 days depending on the termination type) and calculate termination payments that may include unpaid amounts, breakage costs, and either positive or negative market value adjustments. Detail post-termination obligations including final meter readings, final invoicing, return of security, and survival of certain provisions such as confidentiality and indemnification.\n\n**Dispute Resolution and Governing Law**: Designate the governing law, typically the law of the jurisdiction where the facility is located or where the buyer is headquartered. Establish a multi-tiered dispute resolution process beginning with good faith negotiations between senior executives, followed by mediation, and ultimately binding arbitration under recognized rules (ICC, AAA, or LCIA) or litigation in specified courts. Address interim relief, expert determination for technical disputes, and confidentiality of dispute proceedings.\n\n**General Provisions**: Include standard but essential miscellaneous provisions covering assignment rights (typically restricted without consent), amendment procedures (requiring written agreement), notice provisions with specified addresses and methods, entire agreement and merger clauses, severability to preserve the agreement if provisions are found invalid, waiver provisions, counterpart execution, and survival of obligations beyond termination. Address confidentiality obligations, public announcements, and regulatory reporting requirements.\n\n## Document Assembly and Quality Control\n\nOnce all necessary information has been gathered and verified through document research and authoritative external sources, create a comprehensive, professionally formatted Power Purchase Agreement document. The document should be structured with clear hierarchical numbering, cross-references between related provisions, and defined terms consistently capitalized throughout. Include a table of contents, signature blocks for authorized representatives, and schedules or exhibits for technical specifications, pricing tables, form notices, and other detailed information that would otherwise interrupt the flow of the main agreement.\n\nEnsure the final document reflects current market practice, balances the interests of both parties fairly, and complies with applicable regulatory requirements in the relevant jurisdiction. The agreement should be sufficiently detailed to minimize future disputes while remaining clear and accessible to both legal and commercial stakeholders.",
